  Steven King<br>
 just about all of them (except the Dark Tower series. No offense to those who like them but.../em:shudders.<br>
<br>
  L. E. Modesitt, Jr<br>
 He has the &quot;Saga of Recluce&quot; series. Seems very original to me and writing is excellent. Only problem is the &quot;in book&quot; time stream is non-existant in the order of release, but the books are stand alone quality anyway so that's not really an issue.<br>
<br>
  Tadd Williams<br>
 the &quot;Memory, Sorrow and Thorn&quot; series has already been commented on in an earlier post but is worth mentioning again.<br>
<br>
  David Eddings<br>
 his &quot;Mallorean&quot; series is very good, but you may want to read his earlier series &quot;Belgariad&quot; first. Not as good as Mallorean, but still entertaining.<br>
<br>
  Ann Rice<br>
 Another that has been mentioned before, but her whole vampire series and the &quot;Mayfair Witches (I think. been a while since I read them, my sister has them)&quot; series for that matter are both wonderfully well written and are woven together by books like &quot;Lasher&quot; and &quot;Taltos&quot;. Most books written by her under her own name are definately worth reading.<br>
  <br>
  Melanie Rawn<br>
 Another series that seemed refreshing in it's originality. Both her &quot;Dragon Prince&quot; and &quot;Dragon Star&quot; series are related, with &quot;Dragon Prince&quot; being the first set.<br>
<br>
